    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>This Side of Paradise</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dave M O'Neill letter disputes July 23 editorial, which describes affluent residents of the Hamptons as shallow and undeserving</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I take issue with your July 23 editorial ''Hamptons Serenade,'' in which you describe the rich as shallow and undeserving.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I take issue with your July 23 editorial ''Hamptons Serenade,'' in which you describe the rich as shallow and undeserving.</p>
        <p>I have a close friend who is a multimillionaire with a house in the Hamptons. We began in graduate school together in 1960. He dropped out of the Ph.D. program and went to work at an investment bank for $50 a week, while I got my Ph.D.</p>
        <p>Now I make $75,000 a year, and he makes millions.</p>
        <p>Whenever I visit my friend, I feel nothing but pride in his accomplishment, and I feel good about knowing him.</p>
        <p>I don't feel that wealth is ''disorienting'' or ''strangely dislocating.'' I feel that I live in a great and free country -- so free that a young guy like my friend who had no connections can end up a great success.</p>
        <p>DAVE M. O'NEILL  New York, July 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
